ce:section.ce:para:
One interesting finding is that the fluorescence of the Ni-LCDs can be strongly quenched by Cr(VI). Therefore, we believe that the Ni-LCDs can be used to construct a sensor for detecting Cr(VI), and we conducted a detailed study on the sensor's selectivity, anti-interference, and sensitivity. In order to assess the selectivity of the Ni-LCDs for Cr(VI), PL intensity measurements were conducted by mixing the Ni-LCDs with metal ions, anions, amino acids, drugs, and pollutants, respectively. As depicted in Fig. S4A, apart from Cr(VI), the addition of other substances do not alter the PL intensity of the Ni-LCDs. Only Cr(VI) significantly quenches the fluorescence of the Ni-LCDs, indicating that the Ni-LCDs exhibit excellent selectivity for the determination of Cr(VI). When high concentration (0.1 M) of metal ions and anions (Fig. S4B) are present in the Ni-LCDs, the fluorescence of the Ni-LCDs can still be quenched by low concentrations of Cr(VI) (0.01 M), indicating that the Ni-LCDs exhibit outstanding anti-interference performance for Cr(VI) determination. The sensitivity of the Ni-LCDs for the detection of Cr(VI) was further evaluated using fluorescence titration. As shown in Fig. S5A, upon adding the same concentration of Cr(VI) to the Ni-LCDs at various concentrations, the fluorescence of the Ni-LCDs is markedly quenched. The most pronounced quenching occurred at a concentration of 1.5 mg/mL for the Ni-LCDs, thus 1.5 mg/mL was selected as the optimal concentration for the Ni-LCDs in Cr(VI) titration. When the addition of Cr(VI) (0–450 μM), the PL intensity of the Ni-LCDs gradually decreases (Fig. 4A). As depicted in Fig. 4B, when the concentration of the added Cr(VI) ranges from 15 μM to 131 μM, there is a good linear relationship between the concentration of Cr(VI) and (F0
                        F)/F0, where F0 and F represent the PL intensities of the Ni-LCDs in the absence and presence of Cr(VI), respectively. The limit of detection (LOD) for Cr(VI), calculated using a 3-fold standard deviation rule, is determined to be 0.17 μM. We conducts a detailed comparison of the linear range and LOD between the sensor constructed in this study and preciously published CDs-based sensor [28,45–48] for Cr(VI) detection (Table 1
                        ). The results of our constructed method exhibits higher sensitivity and a broader linear range, making it comparable to the reported sensors.
